{"/service/ndnp/mdu/batch_mdu_cumberland_ver02/data/sn89060136/00279522321/1930111401/0396.xml":{"full_text":"THE MIDLAND JOURNAL\nPUBLISHES* EVERY FRIDAY MORNING BY\nE\"W7XfcTGh BEOS.\nRISING BUN CECIL COUNTY MARYLAND\nEntered as Second Class Matter at Post Office In Rising: Sun. Maryland\nUnder Act of Congress of Marsh t, 1879\nINDEPENDENT IN POLITICS AND ALL OTHER SUBJECTS\nTERMS OP SUBSCRIPTION\nONE YEAR, IN ADVANCE $1.50\nSIX MONTHS 1-00\nTHREE MONTHS AO\nSINGLE COPY, S CENTS\nADVERTISING RATES FURNISHED ON APPLICATION\nForeign Advertising Representative\nI THLAMERICAN PRESS ASSOCIATION I\nFRIDAY, NOVEMBER 14, 1930\nIn our election returns, published\nlast week, the figuers we secured\nfrom Elkton showed the election of\nRobert C. Simpers, Republican, for\nCounty Treasurer.\nThe official returns, however,\nshow that Edwin S. Dorcus, Demo-\ncrat, was reelected County Treas\nurer, by 21 votes.\nOur published figuers also showed\nthe electon of Harry H. Howard,\nDemocrat, as County Commissioner\nfrom First Commissioner District.\nThe official returns show that Walter\nC. Miller, Republihan, was elected\nCounty Commissinor from the First\nCommissino'r District.\no\nThe wet press is in high glee over\nthe recent election, but when facts\nare considered, it will be seen just\nhow far they are from any possible\nchange in the Prohibition Act.\nThe fact is that the House of\nRepresentives now holds about 133\nwets, against 302 drys.\nThe 133 wets in the House are go\ning to have some job overcoming\n302 drys, no matter what extravagant\nclaims the wet press makes, which\ndoes everything but state facts about\nProhibition.\no\nAt the present time every state\nlevies a tax against gasoline, ranging\nfrom two to six cents a gallon, and it\nis forcast that the total revenue this\nyear will reach the record sum of\n$550,000,000. Gasoline is subjected\nto the largest sales tax of any com\nmodity, with the possible exception\nof cigaretts.\nHowever, many legislators are not\nsatisfied even with this. Campaigns\nare under way in a number of states,\nnotably Louisiana, West Virginia,\nMaine, Minnesota, Wisconsin, Wash\nington, Nebraska and Colorado, to\npush the tax rates still higher. In\nthe begining, when gas taxes were\nonly one or two cents a gallon, it was\na popular form of taxtion with the\npublic and apparently many officials\nstill believe that \u201cone cent more\nwon\u2019t make any difference.\nThere are unmistakable signs that\nthe public, long patient, is tiring of\nexcessively high rates and perennial\nincreases. The voters of North Da\nkota recently refused to increase the\ntax from three to four cents a gallon,\nand the disapproving voice of the\npublic has been heard in other states.\no\nThe Study of fire control is said to\nbe almost as old as the history of\nman, but in former centuries effort\nwas chiefly given to working out\nways and means of keeping fires\nfrom spreading.\nScientific work designed to prevent\nthe occurrence of fire is of very re\ncent origin and most of the progress\nhas been made in the last three\ndecades.\nOrganized fire prevention, accord\ning to an authority, first came into\nbeing in Ohio. In that state the\nnation\u2019s first fire prevention asso\nciation was formed, the second fire\nmarshal\u2019s law'was passed, the first\nSafe and sane Fourth of July auth\norized and the first state building\ncode committee created. These\nOhio organizations were called to\nother states to assist in starting simi\nlar movements. Fire prevention\nwas given official governmental sup\nport when, in 1920, Woodrow Wilson\nproclaimed Fire Prevention Day,\nwhich has since become Fire Preven\ntion Week.\nOur fire waste is still gigantic,\nbut it is the fault of citizens if they\nhave neglected to learn the rules of\nfire prevention.\no\nRadio, in the United States, has\nbecome one of the greatest forms of\nentertainment. Still an \u201cinfant in\ndustry,\u2019\u2019 it shows vast potentialities\nfor future achievements. Among\nthese, it is hoped, will be its develop\nment as a force in education.\nForeign Advertising Representative\nTHE AMERICAN ''RF.S.S ASSOC* Vi ION\nWITHOUT A COUNTRY\nBy Lucy Meacham Thurston\nAs years go by after the World\nWar and as the great international\nquestions of its aftermath attain\nsome degree of settlement, lesser\nquestions will more and more\nemerge. These will bear upon them\nthe tragedy and heatbreak resulting\nfrom the fearful disasters of warfare.\nThe story of the lost children will\nbe one. The story of the roaming\nRussian children will be another.\nThe story of the men without a\ncountry will be a third. On these\nmany a historical account and many\na novel, realistic as well as romantic,\nwill be, developed within the next\ntwo decades. Such theses afford ro\nmance, adventure, tragedy, with the\nawful background of the greatest\nwar the world has known \u2014may it\nnever known another.\nFor this last theme, the man with\nout a country, some heartrending de\ntails have just been received. They\nwere written by a member of the\nAmerican Friends Service Committee\nwho for a number of years has been\ndoing relief work in Vienna. Her\nwork has brought her into contact\nwith many tragedies. She presents\nsome of these and from those pre\nsented a few of the shorter tragic\ncases are here quoted.\n\u201cI can make no claim to expect\nknowledge on the technical and legal\nside of this difficult problem, but\nspeak as a lay person on whose at\ntention have been forced the diffi\nculties, the possbilities, and the suf\nfering of fellow-beings who, usually\nthrough no fault of their own, are\nmen without a country. In our\nVienna centre case after case has\ncome to us. For three years the\nQuaker group here were occupied\nwith the care of a young man whose\nbirth certificate was lost by the\nBritish authorities, consequently he\nwas unable to obtain Austrian citi\nzenship or to obtain regular employ\nment (paid). Ultimately in this in\nstance the birth certificate was found\nand the young man\u2019s position lega\nlized.\n\u201cBut the large majority of cases\nof home-loss are caused by the\nchanging of frontiers and govern\nments after the war and the large\nscale; destruction which took place,\ndestroying reCoids and making it im\npossible to obtained proof of nation\nality and birthplace by obtaining\ncopies of birth certificates.\nThe saddest cases referred to are\nthose of Huugary and Austria.\nChanging boundarhs and gover\nments account for these. \u201cAll of us\nwho have looked into the problem,\ncontinues the accouut, \u201care well ac\nquainted with this impossible posi\ntion which is forced upon so many\nStaatenlosen and the inhuman treat\nment which is demanded of all the\ncountries concerned alike by the\npresent laws. And workers for in\nternational peace hear especially of\ncases which are the result of declin\ning military service; they turn to us,\nwho are upholding the foward move\nments toward promoting the princi\nples embodied in the Hague Court of\nArbitration, the Leage of Nations\nand the General Peace Pact.\u201d\no\nIf residents of the State are inter\nested in seeing that their evergreens\nget through the winter it will be ne\ncessary, in many cases, to furnish\nthese trees with a good supply of\nwater before heavy freezing weather,\naccording to W. R. Ballard, spec\nialist in Vegetable and Landscape\nGardening for the University of\nMaryland Extension Service. The\nArbor Vitae has been hit particularly\nhard, it is said.\nIf hard rains do not arrive before\nheavy freezing weather, to give the\ntrees a thorough soaking at least\non:e.\nIn addition to the application of\nwater, Mr. Ballard suggests mulch\ning, particularly around such broad\nleaf evergreens as the Azalea, Rhodo\ndendrou anu Mountain Laurel.\nTHE MlfttANtt JOtIRNAI ]FBII)AIfrKoyKMBEB 14, lflSfl\nSAYE YOUE EYES\nBy Dr. J. Fred Andrea*, Sec.\nMd. State Board Optometry\nCORRECT POSTURE\nThe time at which children should\nbe permitted to begin sustained close\nuse of the eyes has a very decided\niufluence upon the strength and use\nfulness of the\u2019eyes in later life. It is\nnot at all uncommon for the eyes,\nduring early life, to become weaken\ned by prolonged reading according\nto Dr. J. Fred Andreae, Secretary of\nthe Maryland Board of Examniers in\nOptometry.\nIt is important that a correct pos\nture be maintained while reading.\nThe work or book should never be\nheld closer than fourteen to sixteen\ninches from the eyes and care should\nbe exercised that the head does not\nincline too far forward, for exces\nsive bending of the neck will impede\nthe return flow of the blood from\nthe head and eyes.\nIf the child persists in holding his\ntext-book too close to the eyes it\nmay be the result of several causes.\nPossibly the seat or desk which he\nis using may not be of the correct\nheight or maybe he has a defect of\nthe eyes which should be corrected\nby proper spectacles.\nThere are few schools in which\nthe desks are correctly adapted to\n1 the varying sizes of children. All\nshould be constructed so that the\ndesk is not too near the eyes nor so\nfar away that irksome stooping is\nnecessary in order to place the eyes\nat the proper distance from their\n1 work.\nAttention must be given to the\nlight in which the eyes are used and\nthere is no other point about which\nneglect is more common. The use\nof the eyes by twilight or faulty arti\nficial light is especially harmful to\nthe eyes of children.\no\ni\nSeal Sale Conference To Be\nHeld In Baltimore\nSeal Sale Chairmen, nurses and\nhealth officers from all sections of\nthe State are expected to attend the\nannual dinner of the Maryland Tuber\nculosis Association in Baltimore, on\nthe evening of November the eigh\n-1 teenth. The dinner will be held at\nthe Rennert Hotel, and is scheduled\nto convene at 7:00 p. m. Reports on\nthe activities of the Assocition for\ntjie year will be read by William B.\nMatthews, Managing Director; Wil\nliam H. Staub, President, and Harry\ni F. Baker, Treasurer. The chief ad\ndress will be delivered by Doctor\nI Kendell Emerson, Managing Direc\ntor of the National Tuberculosis As\nsociation.\nPreceding the dinner a special seal\nsale conference will be held in the\noffices of the Association at 900 Saint\nPaul Street, and will be attended by\nl the county seal sale chairmen. At\nthis meeting plans for the opening\nof the twenty-fourth annual seal sale\ncampaign on Thanksgiving Day will\nbe consumated. This year thirty\nfive million Christmas Seals have\ns been allotted to Maryland. As in the\npast, most ot the counties will con\nconduct their drive by the mail sale.\no\nHOUSEWIVES HEAR TALKS\nON MEAT CUTTING\nTo meet the demands of the consum\ning public for more information icgard\ning small, easily prepared and attractive\ncuts of meat which are rapidly making\nobsolete many meat merchandising\npractices, D. W. Hartzell, of the\nNational Livestock and Meat Board\nspoke to visiting housewives, home\neconomics students and food authorities\non \u201cMeit Cutting Wizard,\u201d November\nio, at the annual meeting of the Balti\nmore Retail Meat Dealers' Association\nof that City.\nAccording to W. E. Hunt, Animal\nand Dairy Husbandry Department of\nthe University af Maryland, there;has\nbeen an ever increasing demand on the\npart of the consumer to know more\nabont the various uses of meat, the\nproper selection for quality and econ\nomy, and the identificrtion of various\ncuts, and it was for the purpose of\nfurnishing this information that the\nmeeting was held. The various dem\nonstrations were made possible\nthrough the cooperation of the National\nLivestock and Meat Board, retail meat\ndealer associations, meat packers, live\nstock producers, and the Uuiversityof\nMaryland.\nThis meeting marks a new step in\neducating the public to better methods\nin food buying. As Mr. Hunt points\nout \u201cin spite of the universal use of\nmeat and the fact that meat purchases\nexceed in value any other food Item, it\nis surprising to note both the lack of\nmeat information and the amount of\nmeat misinformation among consumers.\u201d j\nM\n-S. L J\nse\u00a3sS?L n d\nWHEN far inland, on moun\ntain or plain, you open a\ncan of your favorite fish\n\u2014clams or shrimp, mackerel or\ncod, or any other of the vast\nvariety now packed\u2014perhaps you\nwonder how these denizens of the\nsea retain their fresh-caught fla\nvor, so reminiscent of salt air and\ntide.\nDoes it ever occur to you, as\nyou go about your inland busi\nness that thousands of fishermen\nspend their-, lives along the coast\nearning their livelihood in as\npicturesque and adventurous a\nmanner as the fisher-folk of the\nsea stories that thrilled our youth,\nwhile they pull in the finest fish\nfrom the sea for inland appetites,\nand that these are clapped into\ncans and hermetically sealed\nfaster than they could be cooked\nand served to you at the table?\nThe Popular Clam\nAt any seaside resort, one finds\nduring the summer season, myr\niads of visitors reveling in clams\n\u2014steamed clams, clam broth,\nclams on the half-shell, clam\nchowder, etc. Clams that are\n}ust as excellent as those served\nat seaside stalls are being dug\nfor the canneries, so that enthusi\nasts may eat them all year round.\nThe-clam beds are miles from the\nnearest Tillage, in clean, fine\nwhite sand. Great containers of\nthese fresh dug, fresh shelled\nJuicy clams become immaculately\nclean in vast washing machines\nwhere they are cleansed in their\nown liquor, thus retaining all of\nthe clam strength. And if clam\nchowder happens to be your fa\n-Ite chun dish, you will also be\n-ested to know that the vcge\nFord Digs Two Mile Tunnel for\nA Billion Gallons of Water a Day\nNEARLY a billion gallons of water\na day\u2014more tbau is used by\nthe cities of Detroit, Philadel\nphia, Cincinnati and Washington com\nbltred\u2014will be the capacity of a huge\ntunnel now nearing completion at the\n\u2019Rouge Plant of the Ford Motor Com\n,pany, Dearborn, Michigan.\ni The tunnel will replace the present\nwater intake system which supplies\n;the Ford plants with 500,000,000 gal\n'lons a day. At the same time the com\nipany is remodeling its power bouse to\n;greatly increase the power output.\nI Beth Improvements, costing several\n{million dollars, are being made to en-\nthe production facilities of the\nFord'plant\nSixty Feet Under Ground\nIn constructing the waterway, the\n'largest of its kind ever undertaken by\n!a single business concern, the engi\nneers are burrowing sixty feet under\n{ground for a distance of two and a fifth\n\u25a0miles. They have gone under main\n'highways, railroads, street car tracks,\nbridges, a cemetery and a creek.\nJ One of the most difficult tasks was\nIthat of tunneling under Baby Creek at\n,a point which is crossed by a railroad\n-bridge and where also a large sewer\n:1s under construction by the city of\n-Detroit The piles that provide the\nfoundation for the bridge and those\n!drlven by the company constructing\nthe sewer formed a network on each\nside ot the creek. It was the task of\nthe Ford engineers to burrow under\nthe creek, sewer and bridge, going\nbetween the piles without striking or\nweakening them.\nBoring of tbe tnnnel is accomplished*\nby means of a shield\u2014a large steel\ncylinder fourteen feet long and twenty\nThe New Chevrolet\nChevrolet\u2019s new car for 1931,\npriced substantially below current\nlevels, went on display Saturday\nthroughout the nation.\nHeralded as \"The Great American\nValue,\u201d the new car boasts of two\ninch increase in wheelbase, larger\nand roomier bodies by Fisher -with\nmohair or brodcloth as optional trim\nming, and scores of refinements in\nappearence and performance despite\nthe new prices which bring the level\nfor\ntables for canned clam chowder\nare all pared and cubed by ma\nchinery and only the finest pork\nand seasonings added.\nMore salmon is canned than any\nother kind of fish. Much has al\nready been told of the romance\nof salmon fishing\u2014of the lives\nand fortunes that are risked an\nnually to capture the mysterious\nand adventurous wanderer who\nhas such a strong instinct to re\nturn to his birthplace at spawn\ning season that he leaps cataracts\nin the cold northern streams and\nbraves great hazards to effect that\npurpose. And of how salmon\nfleets carrying complete canneries\nare located out in the mouths of\nrivers whence the salmon starts\nhis Journey Inland, so that the\nfish may be caught at the moment\nwhen it is sleekest and fittest.\nSardines come second to salmon\nin popularity, and are sometimes\ncalled a canner\u2019s invention be\ncause they are really small her\nring a'nd similar fish until they\nenter the can and become \"sar\ndines.\u201d Tuna fish, another can\nner\u2019s invention, was formerly con\nsidered Inedible until one year\nwhen sardines were scarce, can\nners discovered that, by cooking\ntuna, the oil could be removed by\nsteam and when fine salad oil was\nused to replace the natural oil it\nbecame as tender and appetizing\nas the breast of chicken.\nCaviar is the roe of various\nspecies of sturgeon which inhabit\nthe waters of the Atlantic Ocean\nand the waters along the shores\nof Russia, but it is in Russia\nwhere the art of preparing roe\nis one of the oldest industries.\n1a past ages caviar ytaa eaten only.\nv\nI\nThe head of one of the sections of the Ford tunnel showing the machinery used\nto burrow through the ground. In the foreground is one of the concrete bloeke i\nused to line the tunnel which has an inside diameter of fifteen feefe\none feet in outside diameter with a\nsolid steel shell or skin two and a\nfourth laches thick. This shield has a\nbulkhead which is made fast near tbe\nfront end. There are four openings\nthrough which the mud streams, like\ntoothpaste from a tube, aB the shield\nis shoved forward by twenty powerful\nhydraulic jacks.\nWhen the shield has been pushed\nforward sufficiently concrete blocks\ntwo and a half feet wide and five feet\nlong, r-rh wri-hing 3,420 pounds, are\nthan any Chevrolet, four or six, has\never sold.\nDealers throughout the United\nStates put the new models on exhi\nbition Saturday morning for the first\ntime, nearly two months in advance\nof the customary date for the show\ning of the annual new car. This\nmove in advancing the announce\nment date, it was felt by Chevrolet\nofficials, would render a distinct\ncontribution to the cause of general\nbusiness revival by insuring extra\nordinary activity during two normally\ndull business rnonms for the 200,000\nby the highest nobility and the\nwealthy classes', bnt its large pro\nduction in recent years has\nbrought it within the reach of aIL\nCanned Fish Cute Prices\nWith the advent of fish in cans,\nthis healthful food has changed\nfrom a one-day-a-week affair to\nan everyday food\u2014and fishermen\ncan now sell their products more\ncheaply because they know there\nis a steady market. Formerly\nthey had to obtain from one day's\nsales sufficient profit to cover six\nday\u2019s expenses.\nUp in Gloucester, where fisher\nmen go out deep-sea fishing and\nwhere the quest of the sacredcod\nhas been handed down from\nfather to son from the time when\nthe shores of Cape Cod were only\nstraggling fishing villages, the\nwives of the fishermen pride\nthemselves on preparing excellent\nsea food. The following recipe\nsmacks strongly of Gloucester:\nRice Mold and Shrimp Bonce:\nBoil one cup of rice until tender.\nDrain two tablespoons of butter,\ntwo slightly-beaten eggs and two\ntablespoons of evaporated milk.\nPlace into a buttered mold, set in\na pan of hot water and bake until\nfirm for about twenty thirty\nminutes. Meanwhile sautd two;\ntablespoons of chopped opion and\ntwo tablespoons of chopped green\npepper in two tablespoons of but\nter, add two tablespoons of flour,\nstir smooth; then add one No. S\ncan of tomatoes slowly, stirring\nconstantly. Add one 5%-ounce\ncan of shrimps, one-fourth cup of\nsliced ripe olives and salt and\npepper to taste. Unmold the\nand pour over tomato and. shrimp\nsauce. This serves six \u00a3eraou%*V\nplaced to fogm a ring around tba tr*\ncumterence of the tunnel. One at them\nacta as a keystone so that the Uniat\nof concrete, which la eighteen inehaa\nthick, wlthatanda the pressure of the\nearth. After thla steel forma are eet\nup and filled with concrete to form a\nsolid inner lining which la also eighth\neen Inches thick.\nThe present Intake system of the,\nFord plant has a capacity of 600,009,000\ngallons a day. The new tunnel wilt be'\nable to carry 013.600.000 gallons.\npeople throughout United States who\ndepend directly upon Chevrolet for\ntheir livehood.\nBeginning next Sunday, the New\nYork Sunday American will publish a\nnew novel, \"24 Hours\" by Louis Brom*\nfield, Pulitzer prize winner. mas\nter of fiction has written' thrillihg ac\ncount of what happens to a group of\nsociety people whiie the hands go twice\naround the clock. The New York\nAmerican is on sale at all newsstands.\nIf you are unable to obtain it from your\nlocal dealer, send ten cents and we will\nmail a copy, j","height":"25765","width":"17934"}}
